1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:07,000
Stanford University

2
00:00:07,000 --> 00:00:20,000
Okay, let's go to the space-time view of string theory.

3
00:00:20,000 --> 00:00:27,000
What other kind of view could there be but space-time?

4
00:00:27,000 --> 00:00:30,500
But I mean, let's think of the blackboard

5
00:00:30,500 --> 00:00:34,000
as space-time and view what string theory looks like.

6
00:00:34,000 --> 00:00:36,000
First, let's do something simpler first.

7
00:00:36,000 --> 00:00:39,000
Let's just talk about an ordinary particle.

8
00:00:39,000 --> 00:00:43,000
An ordinary particle in

9
00:00:43,000 --> 00:00:47,000
classical mechanics has a trajectory.

10
00:00:47,000 --> 00:00:51,000
Both in non-relativistic physics and relativistic physics, the

11
00:00:51,000 --> 00:00:55,000
trajectory can be described by the three-dimensional position x

12
00:00:55,000 --> 00:00:57,000
as a function of t.

13
00:00:57,000 --> 00:00:59,000
But if you're doing relativity,

14
00:00:59,000 --> 00:01:01,000
there's something which is more convenient,

15
00:01:01,000 --> 00:01:04,500
and that's to take all four components,

16
00:01:04,500 --> 00:01:08,000
space components and time components of position,

17
00:01:08,000 --> 00:01:11,000
call them x mu, and think of

18
00:01:11,000 --> 00:01:14,000
them as a function of a variable

19
00:01:14,000 --> 00:01:18,500
which just denotes and demarks, let's say,

20
00:01:18,500 --> 00:01:23,000
proper time along the trajectory of tau.

21
00:01:23,000 --> 00:01:26,000
Let tau be the proper time along the trajectory.

22
00:01:27,000 --> 00:01:29,500
And then clearly, if you know

23
00:01:29,500 --> 00:01:32,000
the four-dimensional position at every proper time,

24
00:01:32,000 --> 00:01:35,000
or every value of this parameter here, then

25
00:01:35,000 --> 00:01:38,000
you can say exactly where the trajectory went.

26
00:01:38,000 --> 00:01:41,000
So there's a slight, well, maybe more than a

27
00:01:41,000 --> 00:01:44,000
slight, there's a difference of emphasis in non-relativistic physics

28
00:01:44,000 --> 00:01:47,500
where you think of x as a function of time, and in

29
00:01:47,500 --> 00:01:51,000
relativistic physics where you might be inclined to think of x mu,

30
00:01:51,000 --> 00:01:53,500
the four components of position, as a

31
00:01:53,500 --> 00:01:56,000
function of a parameter along the trajectory,

32
00:01:56,000 --> 00:01:59,000
a kind of scalar parameter along the trajectory.

33
00:01:59,000 --> 00:02:02,500
In each case, the motion of a particle is

34
00:02:02,500 --> 00:02:06,000
defined by an action, by a principle of least action.

35
00:02:06,000 --> 00:02:09,000
In the case of a non-relativistic system,

36
00:02:09,000 --> 00:02:12,000
for a free particle, forget potentials, nothing else,

37
00:02:12,000 --> 00:02:14,000
the action, which is usually called s,

38
00:02:14,000 --> 00:02:16,000
I don't know why it's called s,

39
00:02:16,000 --> 00:02:19,000
it's the same label as we use for

40
00:02:19,000 --> 00:02:22,000
entropy, and to make matters worse, in many cases,

41
00:02:22,000 --> 00:02:24,000
entropy and action turn out

42
00:02:24,000 --> 00:02:26,000
to be the same thing, numerically.

43
00:02:26,000 --> 00:02:32,000
But s is action, and for a non-relativistic particle,

44
00:02:32,000 --> 00:02:35,500
it's the integral over time along

45
00:02:35,500 --> 00:02:39,000
the trajectory of the kinetic energy.

46
00:02:39,000 --> 00:02:42,500
One half x dot squared, and I've chosen

47
00:02:42,500 --> 00:02:46,000
the mass of the particle arbitrarily to be one,

48
00:02:46,000 --> 00:02:49,000
because I get tired of writing it.

49
00:02:49,000 --> 00:02:55,000
That's the action, and what do you do with it?

50
00:02:55,000 --> 00:02:57,000
You minimize it. You minimize it

51
00:02:57,000 --> 00:02:59,000
to find the trajectory of the particle.

52
00:02:59,000 --> 00:03:02,500
You minimize it, subject to some end positions,

53
00:03:02,500 --> 00:03:06,000
holding down the end points, you minimize it.

54
00:03:06,000 --> 00:03:09,000
Now that's not what you do in quantum mechanics.

55
00:03:09,000 --> 00:03:12,000
Before we do that, let me discuss the relativistic case.

56
00:03:12,000 --> 00:03:15,000
In the relativistic case, something very similar,

57
00:03:15,000 --> 00:03:18,000
the thing is the action can be taken

58
00:03:18,000 --> 00:03:21,000
to be the integral over tau,

59
00:03:21,000 --> 00:03:24,000
the proper time along the trajectory,

60
00:03:24,000 --> 00:03:28,500
of dx mu by d

61
00:03:28,500 --> 00:03:33,000
tau, dx mu by d tau.

62
00:03:33,000 --> 00:03:35,500
Notice there's one upper index and one lower

63
00:03:35,500 --> 00:03:38,000
index, and you can figure out what that means.

64
00:03:38,000 --> 00:03:41,000
In other words, it looks very, very

65
00:03:41,000 --> 00:03:44,000
much like the non-relativistic kinetic energy formula,

66
00:03:44,000 --> 00:03:46,000
but it means something different.

67
00:03:46,000 --> 00:03:48,500
There are four components of position,

68
00:03:48,500 --> 00:03:51,000
and the time is the proper time,

69
00:03:51,000 --> 00:03:53,000
and what's more,

70
00:03:53,000 --> 00:03:55,500
the time components and the space

71
00:03:55,500 --> 00:03:58,000
components of this expression have different sign.

72
00:03:58,000 --> 00:04:02,000
But apart from that, they look very similar.

73
00:04:02,000 --> 00:04:05,000
And again, what do you do with it?

74
00:04:05,000 --> 00:04:08,000
You minimize it. You minimize it, subject to

75
00:04:08,000 --> 00:04:11,000
the constraint that at the ends of the period,

76
00:04:11,000 --> 00:04:13,500
the particle is at this

77
00:04:13,500 --> 00:04:16,000
space-time point and that space-time point.

78
00:04:16,000 --> 00:04:20,000
So there's a sort of parallel structure,

79
00:04:20,000 --> 00:04:23,000
and basic principle is a principle of least-division.

80
00:04:23,000 --> 00:04:25,000
So you have the first action.

81
00:04:25,000 --> 00:04:27,000
Now in quantum mechanics, you do

82
00:04:27,000 --> 00:04:29,000
something totally different with the action.

83
00:04:29,000 --> 00:04:30,500
What you do with the

84
00:04:30,500 --> 00:04:32,000
action, you ask a different question.

85
00:04:32,000 --> 00:04:36,000
You don't ask, what is the trajectory given to endpoints?

86
00:04:36,000 --> 00:04:40,000
Here you ask, what is the trajectory given to endpoints?

87
00:04:40,000 --> 00:04:43,000
The answer is, of course, a straight line.

88
00:04:43,000 --> 00:04:46,000
In either case, it's a straight line.

89
00:04:46,000 --> 00:04:49,000
It's a straight line through

90
00:04:49,000 --> 00:04:52,000
space and time with constant velocity.

91
00:04:52,000 --> 00:04:53,000
You ask a different question.

92
00:04:53,000 --> 00:04:55,500
You ask, what is the amplitude that

93
00:04:55,500 --> 00:04:58,000
a particle that started at this point,

94
00:04:58,000 --> 00:05:00,500
at time zero or at the beginning of

95
00:05:00,500 --> 00:05:03,000
time, at the start of the time interval,

96
00:05:03,000 --> 00:05:08,000
is detected at that point at a later time?

97
00:05:08,000 --> 00:05:09,000
That's the question you ask.

98
00:05:09,000 --> 00:05:11,000
You don't ask, what's the trajectory in between?

99
00:05:11,000 --> 00:05:13,000
You ask, what's the amplitude for the

100
00:05:13,000 --> 00:05:15,000
particle to go from here to here?

101
00:05:15,000 --> 00:05:19,000
And the answer is,

102
00:05:19,000 --> 00:05:22,000
the amplitude to go from point one to point two,

103
00:05:22,000 --> 00:05:23,500
is the same as the amplitude

104
00:05:23,500 --> 00:05:25,000
of the particle to the point three.

105
00:05:25,000 --> 00:05:29,000
So in either case, you write the action,

106
00:05:29,000 --> 00:05:32,000
you write the exponential of the action,

107
00:05:32,000 --> 00:05:34,500
e to the i, not just any

108
00:05:34,500 --> 00:05:37,000
exponential, but exponential with an i in it,

109
00:05:37,000 --> 00:05:40,000
e to the i times the action,

110
00:05:40,000 --> 00:05:42,000
let's write it out explicitly,

111
00:05:42,000 --> 00:05:46,000
d by dt over one half,

112
00:05:46,000 --> 00:05:51,000
dt dx by dt squared.

113
00:05:51,000 --> 00:05:52,000
This is the equation.

114
00:05:52,000 --> 00:05:56,000
This integral here goes from t1 to t2,

115
00:05:56,000 --> 00:05:58,000
but then you're not finished.

116
00:05:58,000 --> 00:05:59,000
You're not finished.

117
00:05:59,000 --> 00:06:01,500
This expression depends not only on the position

118
00:06:01,500 --> 00:06:04,000
of the particle over here and over here,

119
00:06:04,000 --> 00:06:05,500
but it depends on the position

120
00:06:05,500 --> 00:06:07,000
of the particle everywhere in between.

121
00:06:07,000 --> 00:06:09,000
So what do you do

122
00:06:09,000 --> 00:06:11,000
with it to find the amplitude?

123
00:06:11,000 --> 00:06:16,000
You integrate or you sum over all possible trajectories.

124
00:06:16,000 --> 00:06:19,000
Sum over all trajectories.

125
00:06:19,000 --> 00:06:21,000
Or,

126
00:06:21,000 --> 00:06:23,000
integral, strictly speaking,

127
00:06:23,000 --> 00:06:25,000
over all trajectories.

128
00:06:25,000 --> 00:06:28,000
This is a monstrously complicated thing.

129
00:06:28,000 --> 00:06:33,000
It's not a simple integral that you can put on,

130
00:06:33,000 --> 00:06:36,000
what's his name,

131
00:06:36,000 --> 00:06:39,000
yeah, Mathematica.

132
00:06:39,000 --> 00:06:41,000
It's an infinite dimensional integral,

133
00:06:41,000 --> 00:06:44,000
a continuously infinite dimensional integral.

134
00:06:44,000 --> 00:06:46,000
So it's a mathematical monstrosity.

135
00:06:46,000 --> 00:06:48,000
I mean,

136
00:06:48,000 --> 00:06:49,000
but,

137
00:06:49,000 --> 00:06:51,500
this integral over here is

138
00:06:51,500 --> 00:06:54,000
just the integral along the trajectory.

139
00:06:54,000 --> 00:06:55,000
That's easy.

140
00:06:55,000 --> 00:06:56,000
That's just the action.

141
00:06:56,000 --> 00:06:58,000
But this integral over here

142
00:06:58,000 --> 00:07:01,000
is the sum over all trajectories.

143
00:07:01,000 --> 00:07:04,000
So the particle feels out all trajectories.

144
00:07:04,000 --> 00:07:07,000
It doesn't sample the one of least action.

145
00:07:07,000 --> 00:07:10,000
You integrate over all of them

146
00:07:10,000 --> 00:07:11,000
this expression

147
00:07:11,000 --> 00:07:14,000
to find the amplitude to go from one to two.

148
00:07:14,000 --> 00:07:17,000
That's the quantum mechanical version

149
00:07:17,000 --> 00:07:19,000
of the principle of least action.

150
00:07:19,000 --> 00:07:21,000
It's Feynman path integral.

151
00:07:21,000 --> 00:07:24,000
You do the same thing in either classical mechan-

152
00:07:24,000 --> 00:07:27,000
in either non-relativistic physics

153
00:07:27,000 --> 00:07:29,000
with this expression

154
00:07:29,000 --> 00:07:32,000
or relativistic physics with that expression.

155
00:07:32,000 --> 00:07:35,000
When you calculate in relativistic physics,

156
00:07:35,000 --> 00:07:36,500
the amplitude to go from one

157
00:07:36,500 --> 00:07:38,000
to two is called the propagator.

158
00:07:38,000 --> 00:07:40,000
It's called the propagator for the

159
00:07:40,000 --> 00:07:42,000
particle to go from one to two.

160
00:07:42,000 --> 00:07:45,000
And you do some fancier things with it.

161
00:07:45,000 --> 00:07:48,000
You, for example, consider processes where

162
00:07:48,000 --> 00:07:54,000
particles come in, join, split, and go out.

163
00:07:54,000 --> 00:07:59,000
A similar kind of action

164
00:07:59,000 --> 00:08:02,000
is defined in terms of the action

165
00:08:02,000 --> 00:08:04,000
for each one of these,

166
00:08:04,000 --> 00:08:06,000
what should we call these, each one of these segments.

167
00:08:06,000 --> 00:08:10,000
You add the action together for each segment

168
00:08:10,000 --> 00:08:14,000
and then you don't sum over just a single trajectory.

169
00:08:14,000 --> 00:08:16,000
You sum over all of these trajectories

170
00:08:16,000 --> 00:08:17,000
and on top of everything else,

171
00:08:17,000 --> 00:08:20,000
you integrate over the points

172
00:08:20,000 --> 00:08:23,000
where the trajectories came together.

173
00:08:23,000 --> 00:08:26,000
So you do the same kind of thing

174
00:08:26,000 --> 00:08:30,000
and it gives you a Feynman diagram.

175
00:08:30,000 --> 00:08:31,000
And then at the end,

176
00:08:31,000 --> 00:08:33,000
to make the whole thing even more complicated,

177
00:08:33,000 --> 00:08:37,000
you sum over all Feynman diagrams for a given process

178
00:08:37,000 --> 00:08:39,000
and that gives you the amplitude,

179
00:08:39,000 --> 00:08:40,500
not for a particle to

180
00:08:40,500 --> 00:08:42,000
go from one point to another,

181
00:08:42,000 --> 00:08:44,000
but for a pair of particles

182
00:08:44,000 --> 00:08:46,000
to come in and go out.

183
00:08:46,000 --> 00:08:47,000
All right.

184
00:08:47,000 --> 00:08:56,000
That's the basic setup of Feynman path integrals.

185
00:08:56,000 --> 00:08:58,000
Before we go into string theory,

186
00:08:58,000 --> 00:09:02,000
let me teach you a trick

187
00:09:02,000 --> 00:09:05,000
that physicists use over and over again.

188
00:09:05,000 --> 00:09:07,000
It's a cheat.

189
00:09:07,000 --> 00:09:08,000
It's a cheat.

190
00:09:08,000 --> 00:09:09,000
Can it be justified?

191
00:09:09,000 --> 00:09:13,000
In some special cases, it can be justified.

192
00:09:13,000 --> 00:09:15,000
It turns out it can be more easily justified

193
00:09:15,000 --> 00:09:16,000
in string theory

194
00:09:16,000 --> 00:09:21,000
than in quantum field theory.

195
00:09:21,000 --> 00:09:24,000
But I'll tell you what the trick is.

196
00:09:24,000 --> 00:09:26,000
This kind of integral,

197
00:09:26,000 --> 00:09:27,000
this one, this integral,

198
00:09:27,000 --> 00:09:29,000
is sum over trajectories.

199
00:09:29,000 --> 00:09:32,000
It feels out all trajectories.

200
00:09:32,000 --> 00:09:37,000
Let's even concentrate on the nonrelativistic case.

201
00:09:37,000 --> 00:09:39,000
It feels out trajectories which go like this.

202
00:09:39,000 --> 00:09:42,000
It feels out trajectories which go like this.

203
00:09:42,000 --> 00:09:44,000
It feels out straight trajectories.

204
00:09:44,000 --> 00:09:46,000
And it feels out some wild, wild,

205
00:09:46,000 --> 00:09:50,000
insane trajectories.

206
00:09:50,000 --> 00:09:53,000
Are some of them somehow more important than others?

207
00:09:53,000 --> 00:09:54,000
Of course they are.

208
00:09:54,000 --> 00:09:56,000
The ones which correspond to the classical motion,

209
00:09:56,000 --> 00:09:57,000
the straight line ones,

210
00:09:57,000 --> 00:09:59,000
must be the most important ones.

211
00:09:59,000 --> 00:10:03,000
Otherwise, classical physics wouldn't make sense.

212
00:10:03,000 --> 00:10:06,000
But when you look at the integrand here,

213
00:10:06,000 --> 00:10:09,000
e to the i times anything

214
00:10:09,000 --> 00:10:12,000
always has magnitude what?

215
00:10:12,000 --> 00:10:14,000
One.

216
00:10:14,000 --> 00:10:16,000
So whatever the trajectory is,

217
00:10:16,000 --> 00:10:20,000
they all have equal numerical weight.

218
00:10:20,000 --> 00:10:23,000
They come in with different phases.

219
00:10:23,000 --> 00:10:25,000
The different phases can cancel each other.

220
00:10:25,000 --> 00:10:28,000
If you're adding up numbers on the complex plane,

221
00:10:28,000 --> 00:10:31,000
and all those numbers happen to have unit magnitude,

222
00:10:31,000 --> 00:10:34,000
that doesn't mean they can't cancel.

223
00:10:34,000 --> 00:10:35,000
They can cancel, they can

224
00:10:35,000 --> 00:10:36,000
give rise to a real number,

225
00:10:36,000 --> 00:10:38,000
they can give rise to an imaginary number,

226
00:10:38,000 --> 00:10:40,000
they can do all sorts of things.

227
00:10:40,000 --> 00:10:43,000
But each one of their contributions

228
00:10:43,000 --> 00:10:45,000
is as big as every other contribution.

229
00:10:45,000 --> 00:10:47,000
In that case,

230
00:10:47,000 --> 00:10:51,000
a normal definition of an integral doesn't make sense.

231
00:10:51,000 --> 00:10:53,000
It doesn't converge.

232
00:10:53,000 --> 00:10:56,000
It doesn't converge because the trajectories

233
00:10:56,000 --> 00:10:58,000
which are wildly way out there

234
00:10:58,000 --> 00:11:01,000
and correspond to some very, very distant trajectories,

235
00:11:01,000 --> 00:11:03,000
in some sense,

236
00:11:03,000 --> 00:11:07,000
don't have smaller and smaller amplitude

237
00:11:07,000 --> 00:11:10,000
as the trajectory gets more and more wild.

238
00:11:10,000 --> 00:11:13,000
So, strictly speaking,

239
00:11:13,000 --> 00:11:15,000
these path integrals,

240
00:11:15,000 --> 00:11:20,000
don't really exist as any well-studied mathematical objects.

241
00:11:20,000 --> 00:11:23,000
Okay, so how do we deal with them?

242
00:11:23,000 --> 00:11:27,000
Well, one way of dealing with them

243
00:11:27,000 --> 00:11:29,000
is to be extremely careful,

244
00:11:29,000 --> 00:11:34,000
define integrals in an extremely precise way,

245
00:11:34,000 --> 00:11:39,000
all sorts of reservations and things that are too hard

246
00:11:39,000 --> 00:11:44,000
even for the people who do them to think about.

247
00:11:44,000 --> 00:11:45,000
Really hard.

248
00:11:45,000 --> 00:11:47,000
There's a trick.

249
00:11:47,000 --> 00:11:49,000
There's a trick, and the trick always works.

250
00:11:49,000 --> 00:11:53,000
The trick is one which, to justify it,

251
00:11:53,000 --> 00:11:57,000
is as hard as trying to understand the original integral.

252
00:11:57,000 --> 00:11:59,000
But once you've justified it,

253
00:11:59,000 --> 00:12:01,000
it's the trick which always works

254
00:12:01,000 --> 00:12:03,000
and always gives you the right answer.

255
00:12:03,000 --> 00:12:05,000
So I'm going to tell you what the trick is.

256
00:12:05,000 --> 00:12:06,000
Which shall we take?

257
00:12:06,000 --> 00:12:09,000
Let's take this case here, the relativistic case.

258
00:12:10,000 --> 00:12:13,000
You change the tau variable.

259
00:12:13,000 --> 00:12:14,000
And how do you change it?

260
00:12:14,000 --> 00:12:17,000
You change it very, very simply.

261
00:12:20,000 --> 00:12:24,000
You invent a new variable called s.

262
00:12:24,000 --> 00:12:29,000
And s is just any number times tau.

263
00:12:29,000 --> 00:12:31,000
We'll choose the number alpha later,

264
00:12:31,000 --> 00:12:33,000
to our convenience.

265
00:12:33,000 --> 00:12:35,000
It's just a change of variables.

266
00:12:35,000 --> 00:12:37,000
This is an integration variable.

267
00:12:37,000 --> 00:12:42,000
Incidentally, it goes from tau one to tau two,

268
00:12:42,000 --> 00:12:44,000
and tau one and tau two

269
00:12:44,000 --> 00:12:46,000
are the end points of the trajectory.

270
00:12:47,000 --> 00:12:49,000
But we change variables.

271
00:12:49,000 --> 00:12:50,500
Oh, this s, we shouldn't

272
00:12:50,500 --> 00:12:52,000
confuse this s with the action.

273
00:12:52,000 --> 00:12:54,000
